<main id="main-content">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="content-body">

      <!-- ── Left: prose + example ── -->
      <div class="prose">

        <h2>The formula</h2>
        <p>
          Each project receives a score out of 10, computed as a weighted average of five
          sub-dimension scores (each also 0–10):
        </p>

        <div class="formula-block">
          score = 0.25 × activity<br>
                + 0.30 × replicability<br>
                + 0.15 × community<br>
                + 0.20 × at_specific<br>
                + 0.10 × provenance
        </div>

        <table class="dim-table" aria-label="Scoring dimensions">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Dimension</th>
              <th>Weight</th>
              <th>What it measures</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Activity</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">25%</td>
              <td>Is the project being maintained? Looks at days since last commit, issue response rate, and whether a release shipped in the last year.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Replicability</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">30%</td>
              <td>Can someone actually build or install it? Checks for a bill of materials, build-doc quality, a release artifact, pinned dependencies, and README completeness.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Community</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">15%</td>
              <td>Is the project welcoming to contributors? Looks for a CONTRIBUTING guide, code of conduct, and issue templates.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">AT-specific</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">20%</td>
              <td>Does it meet AT-specific trust signals? Checks for end-user documentation, a feedback channel, "Nothing About Us Without Us" evidence, and known deployment instances.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="dim-name">Provenance</td>
              <td class="dim-weight">10%</td>
              <td>Is the project's origin trustworthy? Looks for an OSI-approved license, associated publication, institutional affiliation, or recognised origin programme.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Worked example: OptiKey</h2>
        <p>
          OptiKey is a free, open-source on-screen keyboard for Windows controlled by eye
          gaze, head tracking, or a standard mouse. Here's exactly how its score of
          <strong>5.2 / 10</strong> was computed from data fetched on 25 June 2026.
        </p>

        <div class="example-card">
          <div class="example-header">
            <div>
              <div class="example-project-name">OptiKey</div>
              <div class="example-project-desc">Eye-gaze on-screen keyboard · GPL-3.0 · github.com/OptiKey/OptiKey</div>
            </div>
            <span class="example-tier-badge">At Risk</span>
          </div>

          <div class="dim-rows">
            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Activity</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.25</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                Last commit was 99 days ago (18 Mar 2026) → <strong>5.0 pts</strong>.
                Issue response rate 54% → min(3.0, 0.54 × 3.34) = <strong>1.8 pts</strong>.
                No release in the last year → <strong>0 pts</strong>.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">6.8 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">contributes 1.70</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Replicability</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.30</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                Release artifact present → <strong>2.0 pts</strong>.
                No BOM → 0 pts. Build docs quality "none" → 0 pts.
                Dependencies pinned: unknown → 0 pts.
                README has installation instructions but missing usage section → 0 pts
                (both required for the bonus point).
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">2.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">contributes 0.60</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Community</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.15</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                CONTRIBUTING file present → <strong>4.0 pts</strong>.
                Issue templates present → <strong>3.0 pts</strong>.
                Code of conduct present → <strong>3.0 pts</strong>.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">10.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">contributes 1.50</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">AT-specific</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.20</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                End-user documentation present → <strong>3.0 pts</strong>.
                Feedback channel present → <strong>2.0 pts</strong>.
                "Nothing About Us" involvement: unverified → 0 pts.
                Known deployed instances: unverified → 0 pts.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">5.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">contributes 1.00</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="dim-row">
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-name">Provenance</div>
                <div class="dim-row-weight">weight 0.10</div>
              </div>
              <div class="dim-row-detail">
                GPL-3.0 is an OSI-approved license → <strong>4.0 pts</strong>.
                No associated publication → 0 pts.
                No institutional affiliation → 0 pts.
                No origin programme → 0 pts.
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="dim-row-score">4.0 / 10</div>
                <div class="dim-row-contrib">contributes 0.40</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="example-total">
            <div>
              <div class="example-total-label">Final score</div>
              <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text-muted);margin-top:4px;">
                1.70 + 0.60 + 1.50 + 1.00 + 0.40
              </div>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="example-total-score">5.20 / 10</div>
              <div class="example-total-tier">Tier: At Risk</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>
          OptiKey's community health is exemplary — CONTRIBUTING file, code of conduct, and
          issue templates all present. Its score is dragged down by <strong>replicability</strong>:
          there's no bill of materials (it's software, so that's expected) and the README
          covers installation but not end-to-end usage. Adding a usage section to the README
          and pinning dependencies would move replicability from 2.0 to at least 3.0,
          pushing the total score above the 5.5 Stable threshold.
        </p>

        <h2>Tier thresholds</h2>
        <p>
          Once the score is computed, the tier is assigned using a first-match rule applied
          in this order:
        </p>

        <table class="tier-table" aria-label="Health tier thresholds">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Tier</th>
              <th>Condition (first match wins)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.52 0.14 22)"></span><span class="tier-label">Archived</span></td>
              <td>Activity score = 0 AND last commit more than 3 years ago.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.52 0.16 142)"></span><span class="tier-label">Thriving</span></td>
              <td>Score ≥ 7.5</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.50 0.14 245)"></span><span class="tier-label">Stable</span></td>
              <td>Score ≥ 5.5</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.72 0.13 83)"></span><span class="tier-label">Dormant</span></td>
              <td>Activity ≤ 2.0 AND replicability ≥ 5.0 — the project still builds even if it's not actively maintained.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="tier-swatch" style="background:oklch(0.62 0.17 47)"></span><span class="tier-label">At Risk</span></td>
              <td>Everything else — below Stable and not cleanly Dormant.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>
          The Dormant tier exists to distinguish projects that are quietly stable from ones
          that are decaying. A project with no recent commits but a solid, pinned,
          reproducible build is more useful than a nominally "active" project you can't
          actually install.
        </p>

        <h2>Limitations</h2>
        <p>The score is a heuristic, not a verdict. It cannot see:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hardware quality</strong> — a BOM can exist and still describe a poorly-designed device. We can check that documentation is present; we can't check that it is accurate or safe.</li>
          <li><strong>Documentation in languages other than English</strong> — we track <code>documentation_languages</code> as metadata, but non-English docs don't receive extra weight yet.</li>
          <li><strong>Actual usability for disabled people</strong> — the "Nothing About Us" field captures known co-design involvement, but the absence of that signal doesn't mean disabled people weren't involved.</li>
          <li><strong>Private forks or deployment</strong> — a project with no public stars could be deployed widely in a hospital system; we have no visibility into that.</li>
          <li><strong>Regulatory or safety certification</strong> — ISO 9999 codes are recorded as metadata but don't factor into the score.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          We plan to revisit the formula weights and add new signals (e.g. documentation
          language breadth, co-design depth) in future versions. Formula changes will
          increment <code>SCORING_VERSION</code> and be announced in the changelog.
        </p>

      </div>

      <!-- ── Right: sidebar ── -->
      <aside class="sidebar" aria-label="Methodology quick links">

        <div class="sidebar-card">
          <div class="sidebar-card-title">Formula at a glance</div>
          <p><code>score = 0.25×activity + 0.30×replicability + 0.15×community + 0.20×at_specific + 0.10×provenance</code></p>
          <p>Each sub-dimension is scored 0–10. Final score is rounded to two decimal places.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="sidebar-card">
          <div class="sidebar-card-title">Version</div>
